<p style='margin-top: 0px;'>Mary Ann died, with her father by her side, on 11 October 1870, just 15 days short of her eighteenth birthday.
    We have a copy of
    <span   style="text-decoration: underline; background-color: AntiqueWhite; color: sienna;"
            title = "View certificate"
            onclick="viewImage('images/Mary Ann DCert 1870.jpg');">the death certificate</span>, which gives the cause
    of death as pericarditis and exhaustion, one or both of these spanning a period of 14 days - so perhaps that&#39;s 
	how long she had been laid up at home. She died at 1 Hill Place, just off Whit Lane to its east. By the age of 17, it&#39;s 
	almost certain that she had been working for some time in one or more of the local industrial establishments, and in the 
	light of what we learned later, it&#39;s not inconceivable that she was worked to death. But perhaps she had had a heart 
	defect from birth, who knows?</p>

	<p>She died just a few months after the loss of the infant Charles, leaving her younger brother James nearing his sixteenth birthday, the next, John, having just had his eleventh birthday, and her
    youngest brother Richard aged seven. We do not know for sure where she was buried, although given what we learned later, it 
	would almost certainly have been in a public grave, probably at Weaste cemetery. The definitive record would be held at the 
	office of Salford Bereavement Services, now located at Agecroft cemetery.</p>

<p>Many families could simply not afford to purchase a family grave and stone memorial, and we suspect
    that John and Bridget were no exception. Despite this, there are to this day two stone memorials of Mary Ann&#39;s short life at
    Weaste cemetery. One, shown here, is a public memorial to the many thousands who were buried there in locations for which no records remain. The
    other will emerge very soon as our story progresses.</p>
<br>
<u>The 1871 census</u>
<p style="margin-top: 0;">So at the second census of John and Bridget's family on 2 April 1871, there were still five people in
