<p style = "margin-top:0px;">Although the stone is severely delaminated, enough remains to confirm our interpretation of the story.
    I spoke to the oldest of the firms of stonemasons still associated with the two cemeteries at Weaste and Agecroft. This firm used to have
    an office on Eccles New Road near to Weaste and to the (now demolished) church of All Souls and St John Vianney (which then serviced Weaste
    cemetery). Sadly, there are no business records left from that era. But from our visits to the cemetery, the headstone is of a standard
    design very common in that sector of the graveyard. The stonemasons immediately identified my description as the "gothic" style. For the
    Irish immigrants, the usual inscription around the head of the stone was <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>
	"of your charity, pray for the souls"</i></b></span>.</p>

<p>Below this exhortation to pray and the faint outline of the cross below, we can see the words
    <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>
	"Ann Noonan"</i></b></span>, positioned so as to suggest strongly that the word "Mary" is missing. Then
    <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>"11th 1870"</b></i></span>, and on the next line the end of "aged xxx
    y<span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>ears"</b></i></span>. Clearly, Mary Ann's death on 11 October 1870.
    Next another <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>"oonan"</i></b></span>, followed by something
    <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>"25th 1874"</i></b></span>, and finally
    <span style="font-family: Georgia;  color: DarkSlateGrey;"><b><i>"14 years"</i></b></span>. Equally clearly, young John's death on
    February 25th 1874. But not a single inscription beyond 1874.</p>

<p>The burial records now held at Agecroft leave no doubt that Grave C20-2447 Weaste was first opened in 1874 for young John Noonan&#39;s
    burial. This means that, on Friday 27 February 1874, with almost no notice,
    a large sum of money was made available to acquire an expensive burial-plot at Weaste. Then a headstone was purchased and an
    inscription commissioned, with the words surely chosen by John and Bridget.  And their choice was to place the name of their daughter,
    by then dead for over three years, at the top of that headstone. This is Mary Ann&#39;s second stone memorial at Weaste cemetery, even though
    her mortal remains were never buried under it.</p>

<p>Here, I fall back on what some might term speculation - I was going to say "pure", but there are in fact a number of scraps of
    circumstantial evidence supporting the speculation. For myself, though, as I&#39;ve researched the story and repeatedly turned it over
    in my mind, the speculation has become a deep and instinctive conviction. Peter Reid&#39;s Dye Works
    on Indigo Street - no doubt named after the works - was only a short distance from 65 Whit Lane. The terrible accident would have become
    known to everyone working there within minutes, and a runner would have been sent to Whit Lane, so that his parents would have heard the news
    only a few minutes later. Both the workforce and the parents would have been utterly horrified and filled with an indignant anger. The
    general view held by the workers of their employer Mr Reid is unknown, but however good relations might have been in normal times, they
    would have been precarious on the day of the accident. Peter Reid almost immediately decided to meet young John&#39;s funeral costs in
    full - however successful the greengrocery business, it would not run to the purchase of a burial-plot at Weaste with no notice
    whatsoever.</p>

<p>But this leads us into deeper levels of accumulated feelings and perceptions around the lives being lived on the streets of Salford in
    the years following the start of the big surge of Irish migrations triggered by the crop failures in the the second half of the 1840s.
    The loss of John would have been a shocking reminder of the loss of Mary Ann just a few years earlier, whatever the immediate causes of her
    death had seemed to be. That wound would still have
    been raw, together with the memory that they had not been able to afford a grave, headstone and proper burial for her. Nor had they
    been able to afford the same for Sarah Jane, the first John, Joseph or Charles. No doubt infant deaths were in those days something that it was
    accepted were sadly unavoidable, but none of the four had had a "personal" burial or a headstone. And what did it take for people like
    John and Bridget to acquire a family burial-plot? Why, only that their teenage son should be run through the steam-driven mangle in
    one of the industrial palaces which were the only places, really, where a person could earn a living. Little wonder that Mary Ann&#39;s
    name should have been placed at the top of the headstone.</p>

<p>Perhaps, though, we should be offering thanks to Peter Reid for his generous and warm-hearted gesture? Heaven knows what his feelings
    were about the accident which had happened in his factory. He may have carried a heavy burden of guilt for the rest of his life. Perhaps
    John senior and Bridget and young John&#39;s erstwhile colleagues on the shop-floor felt a genuine gratitude for the gesture. I will
    try to avoid stooping into the gutter where the politics of envy thrive, but we could take a quick moment to have a glance at how the
    other half - in the form of Peter Reid - lived in those days. Here is a <a href="dig1a"
            title = "Take the digression">brief digression on the subject on Peter Reid&#39;s life
	and background</a>, if you are interested.</p>
<br>
<u>Handing on the baton</u>

<p style = "margin-top:0;">The next visible event in the Noonan family history is another sad step in the continuing shrinkage of
    that family. John Noonan senior gave up the ghost - it seems very suddenly - on 29 December 1877, four days after Christmas and just
    a month or two before the fourth anniversary of John junior&#39;s death.  Before we obtained <span
	        style="text-decoration: underline; background-color: AntiqueWhite; color: sienna;"
            title = "View certificate"
            onclick="viewImage('images/John Noonan DCert 1877.jpg');">his death certificate</span>, I had allowed
    some sarcasm and flippancy to creep into my writing. I speculated that John could have died from a broken heart or perhaps he had
    just learned that the Reid family was moving into the centre of Charlestown (where we know they had arrived by April 1881). If
    anything, the certificate serves to reinforce rather than  expunge these thoughts. John died of apoplexy, which to me has the
    natural meaning of an irrepressible eruption of bottled-up rage. Medically speaking, it was more likely to mean a stroke brought
    on by a burst blood vessel in the brain, but isn't this something that bottled-up rage would tend to lead to anyway? Since John
    junior had died, the family had moved house again - they were now at 71 Whit Lane three doors away from 65. Bridget was present
    at the death, and signed with an X to this effect. John's age was recorded as 45, and I believe 1832 is indeed our best estimate
    of his year of birth. His son James was then 23 years old and Richard 14. John senior was buried at Weaste on 2 January 1878 in the same
    grave as John junior, but no inscription was added to the headstone. What a festive season that must have been.
</p>

<p>So by the time we reach the next census date in 1881, the family part of the household is reduced to three (although Bridget has
    taken in some boarders, presumably with the main purpose of making up the income).</p>



